---
title: Washing the Dishes to Wash the Dishes
subtitle: On being present to whatever is in front of you.
excerpt: A short passage from The Miracle of Mindfulness that says more about meditation than most long explanations.
meta: Thích Nhất Hạnh · The Miracle of Mindfulness · 1975
order: 1
---

<blockquote class="quote-display">
  <p>
    While washing the dishes one should only be washing the dishes, which means that
    while washing the dishes one should be completely aware of the fact that one is
    washing the dishes. At first glance, that might seem a little silly: why put so
    much stress on a simple thing? But that's precisely the point. The fact that I am
    standing there and washing these bowls is a wondrous reality. I'm being completely
    myself, following my breath, conscious of my presence, and conscious of my thoughts
    and actions. There's no way I can be tossed around mindlessly like a bottle slipping
    back and forth on the waves.
  </p>
  <cite>— Thích Nhất Hạnh, <em>The Miracle of Mindfulness</em> (1975)</cite>
</blockquote>

<p>
  The passage comes early in a short book Thích Nhất Hạnh wrote as a letter to a fellow
  monk managing a peace delegation in the United States — someone with almost no time
  to practice. The dishes are not a metaphor. He means the actual dishes, the actual
  water, the actual moment.
</p>

<p>
  What makes this more than a pleasant sentiment is the implicit diagnosis of what normally
  happens while washing dishes: the mind is somewhere else entirely. Planning the next hour,
  rehearsing a conversation, waiting for the task to be over so that real life can resume.
  The dishes become an obstacle between here and there. Thích Nhất Hạnh's point is that
  there is no <em>there</em> — or rather, that treating the present moment as a corridor
  to somewhere more important is the exact structure of the problem the teaching is trying
  to address.
</p>

<p>
  The phrase "tossed around mindlessly like a bottle slipping back and forth on the waves"
  is precise in a way that rewards attention. The bottle is not suffering dramatically. It
  is just going wherever the water takes it, without any say in the matter. That is what
  inattention looks like from the outside — and, eventually, from the inside too.
</p>

<p>
  This is also a gentle entry point into what <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
  actually means in practice. Not a special state, not the absence of thought, but the
  simple fact of knowing what you are doing while you are doing it. The dishes are there.
  The water is warm. That is enough — if you are actually there to notice.
</p>
